We use the Stable Diffusion v1.51.51.51.5 inpainiting model as our baseline diffusion model. The training parameters for the CholecSeg8K dataset are shown in Tab. 9. The dataset consists of 5080508050805080 images for training, 2000200020002000 images for testing and 1000100010001000 images as validation set. We resized all the images to 512512512512x512512512512. Depending upon our initial experiments, we noticed for the abdominal wall that the generated images either suffered from creating the correct texture or having semantic leakage i.e., texture of other organs being replaced. One reason could be the variance in the lighting conditions. To account for this, be opted for the v𝑣vitalic_v-prediction loss from [50]. This has shown to improve image quality in low lighting. For the HeiSurf dataset, we used the parameters as the CholecSeg8K dataset. All the diffusion models were trained 1500150015001500 steps. The generated images were evaluated at every 500 steps using different metrics and visual examination. The pre-trained soft edge ControlNet was used to control the anatomy shape during the inference process. We sampled images from the inpainted model with pre-trained CN with DDIM [59] scheduler using 30303030 steps. A similar process was used for the DSAD dataset where a guidance scale of 5.55.55.55.5 was used for all the organs. For this dataset, we did not use the v-prediction method for training any specific organ. To reduce the overhead in the inference pipeline, we used the fast MultiStep [72] sampler in Stage-4444 with SDEdit for image enchancement. We opted for 5−8585-85 - 8 steps for inconsistency removal process. Since the HeiSurf dataset had smaller image of images, we trained only the ControlNet-SE and T2i-Adapter-CY models on this dataset.
